1

00:00:04,219  -->  00:00:07,710
Let&#39;s say you&#39;ve just finished running an experiment,

2

00:00:07,710  -->  00:00:09,750
where you send out a promotional coupon to

3

00:00:09,750  -->  00:00:14,324
a mailing list in order to see if it drives up sales in your online store.

4

00:00:14,324  -->  00:00:16,800
Going through the statistical analysis,

5

00:00:16,800  -->  00:00:19,875
you find that there is a statistically significant effect.

6

00:00:19,875  -->  00:00:22,710
People who received the coupon were five percent more

7

00:00:22,710  -->  00:00:25,925
likely to make purchases than those that did not.

8

00:00:25,925  -->  00:00:30,000
Does this mean that we should send out the coupon on a broader scale?

9

00:00:30,000  -->  00:00:31,940
Not necessarily.

10

00:00:31,940  -->  00:00:35,120
If the cost of sending out the coupon and reduced revenue

11

00:00:35,119  -->  00:00:38,390
from the coupon outweigh the revenue that was gained without it,

12

00:00:38,390  -->  00:00:41,634
then it doesn&#39;t make sense to use the coupon on a broad scale.

13

00:00:41,634  -->  00:00:46,729
This is an example of the importance of considering practical significance.

14

00:00:46,729  -->  00:00:50,869
Practical significance refers to the level of effect that you want to see in

15

00:00:50,869  -->  00:00:53,419
your experiment in order for it to make sense

16

00:00:53,420  -->  00:00:56,715
for your manipulations to actually be implemented.

17

00:00:56,715  -->  00:00:59,035
As suggested by the example,

18

00:00:59,034  -->  00:01:02,244
simply because your experiment is statistically significant,

19

00:01:02,244  -->  00:01:04,789
does not necessarily mean that it&#39;s also

20

00:01:04,790  -->  00:01:08,240
practically significant and worth following through.
